article.description:
Ryan Bowen's layup just before the final buzzer
gave the Denver Nuggets an 80-79 victory over the Phoenix Suns in a
sloppily played game Saturday night.
article.headline: Bowen's layup at buzzer stuns Phoenix
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- A player with a quarterback's arm and a teammate not known for his offense combined to give the Denver Nuggets a dramatic 80-79 victory over the Phoenix Suns on Saturday night.
Bowen

Donnell Harvey flung the ball all the way downcourt and Ryan Bowen made a layup just before the final buzzer to give the Nuggets their second last-second win in as many nights. "When I threw it, it was right on the money and he got the layup for the win,'' the left-handed Harvey said. "I used to play quarterback in high school, so it was neat to have a flashback.'' Bowen's basket came after the Suns appeared to have won the game on Shawn Marion's slam with six-tenths of a second remaining after a missed shot by Stephon Marbury. The Suns began celebrating, but too early. At first, it was uncertain whether Bowen had gotten the shot off in time, but the officials used instant replay to confirm the basket was good, making it the Nuggets' turn to celebrate. On Friday, Denver defeated the Los Angeles Clippers 72-70 on James Posey's buzzer-beater. Before Harvey's pinpoint pass to the alert Bowen, Nuggets coach Jeff Bzdelik tried to call timeout. The officials didn't see him and neither did Harvey. "I would have fined myself if they had called a timeout,'' the relieved Bzdelik said. If there had been a timeout, Bowen wouldn't even have been in the game. "I told the coach that it was a great move leaving me in for offense; usually he puts me in for defense,'' Bowen said, laughing. "That was the first time I ever hit a game-winning basket at any level. It was nice.'' Bowen wasn't sure he would get close enough to the basket for an easy shot. "I saw him throw it, but I didn't want to catch it at 3-point range,'' he said. "So I kept going. "I knew it was in. When I let it go, I saw the red light. I thought it was good ... but maybe not." Marbury admitted that the Suns began celebrating too early. "We thought we had won the game,'' he said. "But it's never over until the horn sounds. They made a great play.'' Posey led the Nuggets with 20 points, Juwan Howard had 16 and Harvey finished with 13 points and nine rebounds. Marion was high scorer for Phoenix with 19 points and Marbury had 13 points and a season-high 14 assists. The Nuggets trailed 67-57 early in the fourth quarter before reeling off 12 consecutive points and taking their first lead since the opening period. After that, the lead changed hands seven times and the score was tied three times. Phoenix took its biggest lead, 46-33, in the third period, but the Nuggets got back into the game with 10 straight points, including four each by Posey and Howard. The second period was a comedy of errors -- airballs, blown layups, turnovers, missed free throws, errant passes and fouls -- as the Suns scored only 16 points and the Nuggets had 13, giving Phoenix a 39-31 halftime lead. The Suns went without a field goal from 6:56 remaining until four-tenths of a second was left before halftime when Dan Langhi hit a jumper from the top of the key. Denver didn't take its first foul shot of the game until five minutes remained in the second quarter, then missed its first four before Junior Harrington converted two with 2:43 to go. Game notes
The Nuggets played without two of their key players, both of whom are on the injured list: starting point guard Chris Whitney, out with a sprained left ankle, and center-forward Marcus Camby, sidelined with an ailing right hip that required surgery. Whitney has missed seven games and Camby has not played this season. ... With Whitney and Camby missing, the Nuggets' active roster has a combined 21 years of NBA experience among 12 players, including Juwan Howard, who is in his ninth season. ... Suns forward Tom Gugliotta was out with a strained right foot and was replaced in the starting lineup by rookie Amare Stoudemire. ... Phoenix coach Frank Johnson turned 44 Saturday.
